of coronavirus in Spain |access-date=1 April 2020 |publisher=[[RTVE]] |language=Spanish}}\n** {{cite web |url=https://elpais.com/sociedad/2020/03/30/actualidad/1585589827_546714.html |title=Casos confirmados de coronavirus en Espa\u00f1a y en el mundo |trans-title=Confirmed cases of coronavirus in Spain and in the world |access-date=1 April 2020 |publisher=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |language=Spanish}}\n** {{cite web |url=https://covid19.isciii.es/ |title=Situaci\u00f3n de COVID-19 en Espa\u00f1a |trans-title=Situation of COVID-19 in Spain |access-date=1 April 2020 |publisher=[[Carlos III Health Institute|ISCIII]] |language=Spanish}}\n* Government-issued information:\n** {{cite web |url=https://www.mscbs.gob.es/en/profesionales/saludPublica/ccayes/alertasActual/nCov-China/home.htm |title=Enfermedad por nuevo coronavirus, COVID-19 |trans-title=New coronavirus disease, COVID-19 |access-date=1 April 2020 |publisher=[[Ministry of Health (Spain)|Ministry of Health]] |language=Spanish}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n<!-- AFAIK [[Wikipedia:Related Pages extension]] is inactive, so this can most probably be removed:\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Community of Madrid}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asturias}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Canary Islands}}\n{{#related:2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory}}\n-->\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Spain]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Spain]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Spain]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in Spain|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Spain|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Spain|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "ChaTo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Spain"}
{"title_page": "Islam and humanity", "text_new": "<!-- keep the tone neutral, refrain from inserting own religious biases e.g. SAW/PBUH etc. Provide both sides of the argument including sanction of abuse, pedophilia, sexual slavery, subjugation of women, inhumane treatment of non-Muslims, wife beating, child abuse in Islam-->\n{{Islam}}\n'''Islamic teachings on humanity and human welfare''' have been codified in its central religious book known as the [[Quran]], which the [[Muslim]]s believe was [[Wahy|revealed]] by [[God]] for the mankind. These teachings have often been exemplified by Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]] as displayed in his [[Hadith|sayings]] and [[sunnah|practices]]. To the Muslims, Islam is what the Quran has instructed to do and how Muhammad has put them into practice. Thus, the understanding of any Islamic topic generally rely on these two..\n\n==Social welfare in Islam==\nIn Islamic tradition, the idea of social [[welfare]] has been presented as one of its principal values,<ref name=Stefon92>{{cite book |editor=Matt Stefon|title=Islamic Beliefs and Practices |url=https://archive.org/details/islamicbeliefspr0000stef|url-access=registration|publisher=[[Britannica Educational Publishing]] |year=2010 |location=[[New York City|New York]] |isbn=978-1-61530-060-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/islamicbeliefspr0000stef/page/92 92]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Palmer |first=Michael D. |title=Religion and Social Justice |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4W4fg2xZAOwC&pg=PA159 |accessdate=22 January 2016 |year=2012 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=9781405195478 |page=159}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://muslimcanada.org/welfare.htm |title=Social Welfare: A Basic Islamic Value |author=Anis Ahmad |date=1997 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> and the practice of social service at its various forms has been instructed and encouraged. A Muslim's [[D\u012bn|religious life]] remains incomplete if not attended by service to humanity.<ref name=Stefon92/> The following verse of the Quran is often cited to encapsulate the Islamic idea of social welfare:<ref>{{cite book |first1=John |last1= Corrigan |first2=Frederick |last2= Denny |first3=Martin S |last3= Jaffee |title=Jews, Christians, Muslims: A Comparative Introduction to Monotheistic Religions |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VahYCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA245 |accessdate=22 January 2016 |year=2016 |publisher=Routledge |location= |isbn=9781317347002 |page=245}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|It is not righteousness that ye turn your faces towards East or West; but it is righteousness to believe in Allah and the Last Day, and the Angels, and the Book and the Messengers; to spend of your substance, out of love for Him, for your kin, for orphans, for the needy, for the wayfarer, for those who ask, and for the ransom of slaves; to be steadfast in prayer, and practice regular charity, to fulfill the contracts which we have made; and to be firm and patient, in pain (or suffering) and adversity, and throughout all periods of panic. Such are the people of truth, the God fearing (Quran {{cite quran|2|177|s=ns|b=n}}).}}\n\nSimilarly, duties to [[parent]]s, [[Neighbourhood|neighbors]], relatives, sick people, the old, and the [[minority group]] have been defined in Islam. In a long [[hadith]] recorded in Hadith Qudsi (sacred hadith), it is said that God, on the [[Last Judgment|Day of Judgment]], will be displeased with those who do not care for the sick people, and who do not give food to those who ask. God will interrogate them and demand explanation from them. This hadith is seen as a reminder of human beings\u2019 obligation to respond to the needs of others.<ref>{{cite book |last= J. Cornell |first=Vincent |title=Voices of Islam: Voices of life : family, home, and society |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ixO4b6jlbLYC&pg=PA129 |accessdate= |year=2007  |publisher= Greenwood Publishing Group|location= |isbn=9780275987350 |page=129}}</ref> The individual, [[Family|the family]], the [[State (polity)|state]], and the [[Non-governmental organization]]s \u2014 all are responsible for the performance of social responsibilities, and for the promotion of social welfare. The Quran tells that the believers have been sent for the betterment of mankind, that they will promote what is good, and prevent what is wrong ({{cite quran|3|110|s=ns|b=n}}).<ref>[[Maariful Quran]] (exegesis of the Quran) by [[Muhammad Shafi Usmani]]. [[Karachi]]. Chapter 3.</ref> However, this is to be carried out in the best possible manner: no individuals honor should be injured, and no harm should arise out of it.<ref>Hashmi, Sohail H., ed. (2009). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=5LmXFpnp_bMC&pg=PA68 Islamic Political Ethics: Civil Society, Pluralism, and Conflict]''. Princeton University Press. p. 68. {{ISBN|9781400825370}}.</ref> In Islamic tradition, the family has a greater role to play in properly educating its members and providing them with moral schooling so as to make them good members of society. The state has the responsibility to preserve the [[human rights]] of its [[citizen]]s while various non-government institutions in a [[civil society]] are to carry out public services and [[Charity (practice)|charitable works]].<ref>Hashmi (2009), p. 68-9</ref>\n\n==Rights of various groups in Islam==\n===Rights of the parents and relatives===\nIn Islam, special importance has been attached to the service and rights of [[parent]]s. Respecting and obeying one's parents has been made a [[Fardh|religious obligation]], and ill-treatment to them is [[Haraam|forbidden in Islamic jurisprudence]] and Islamic tradition. With regard to the rights of parents, the Quranic injunction is to behave well with then, to take care of them especially in their old age, not to be rude to them, and to show highest respect to them.<ref>[[Muhammad Shafi Deobandi|Mufti Muhammad Shafi]]. ''[[Maariful Quran]]''. English trans. By [[Muhammad Taqi Usmani]]</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor=Juan E. Campo |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Islam |publisher=[[Facts On File]] |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-8160-5454-1|page=136}}</ref> <ref group=\"n\">The [[Quran]] says in this regard: \"Your Lord has decreed that you worship none but Him, and do good to parents. If any one of them or both of them reach old age, do not say to them a word of contempt and do not scold them, and address them with respectful words, and submit yourself before them in humility out of compassion, and say, \"My Lord, be merciful to them as they have brought me up in my childhood\"\"  ({{cite quran|17|23-24|s=ns|b=n}}).</ref> This injunction is to be applied regardless of parents' religious identity, that is, a Muslim person is to respect and serve their parents whether they be Muslim or non-Muslim.<ref>Cornell (2007), p. 97</ref> Hadith literature provides plenty of instances where Muhammad has commanded [[Sahabah|his companions]] to be good and kind to their parents and to serve them in the best possible manner.<ref>{{cite book |last= Cornell |first=Vincent J. |title=Voices of Islam: Voices of life : family, home, and society |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ixO4b6jlbLYC&pg=PA95 |accessdate=12 February 2016 |year=2007  |publisher= Greenwood Publishing Group |location= |isbn= 9780275987350 |page=95}}</ref> Insulting or misbehaving with one's parents has been declared a major sin.<ref>Cornell (2007), p. 98</ref> Mother, however, has been given priority over father in terms of receiving respect and service from children. The high status of mother in Islam is best exemplified by the saying of Muhammad that \"paradise is at the feet of your mothers\".  Similarly, importance has also been attached to the rights of [[Kinship|relatives]]. A two-fold approach is generally prescribed with regard to the duties to the relatives: keeping good relation with them, and offering financial help if necessary.<ref>{{cite book |last=Al-Sheha |first=Abdur Rahman |title=Human Rights in Islam and Common Misconceptions |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZRqe3iPwsTkC&pg=PA65 |location=Riyadh |pages=65}}</ref> Maintaining good relation with one's relatives has been emphasized, and severing ties with them has been admonished. It is said in the [[hadith]], \"The person who severs the bond of kinship will not enter Paradise.\"<ref>{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|8|73|13}}</ref>\n\n===Rights of the neighbors===\n{{Rquote|right|Gabriel kept on recommending me about treating the neighbors in a kind and polite manner, so much so that I thought that he would order me to make them my heirs.|'''[[Muhammad in Islam|Muhammad]]'''|''{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|8|73|44}}''}}\n\nRegardless of a [[Neighbourhood|neighbor]]'s religious identity, Islam tells the Muslims to treat their neighboring people in the best possible manners and not to cause any difficulty to them.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Abdelwahab |editor1-last=Bouhdiba |title=The Individual and Society in Islam: Volume 2 of The different aspects of Islamic culture |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xek6yZPAQjAC&pg=PA238 |accessdate= |year=1998 |publisher=UNESCO |location= |isbn=9789231027420 |page=238}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=al-Sheha |first=Abdur Rahman |title=Human Rights in Islam and Common Misconceptions |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZRqe3iPwsTkC&pg=PA75 |accessdate= |year= |publisher= |location=Riyadh |isbn= |pages=74\u20135}}</ref> The Quran tells the Muslims to stand by their neighbors in the latter's  everyday needs. Muhammad is reported as saying, \"A man is not a believer who fills his stomach while his neighbor is hungry.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sunnah.com/adab/6/12 |title=Al-Adab Al-Mufrad 112}}</ref> One typical [[hadith]] on neighbors reads as follows: Narrated Abu Shuraih: The Prophet said, \"By Allah, he does not believe! By Allah, he does not believe! By Allah, he does not believe!\" It was said, \"Who is that, O Allah's Apostle?\" He said, \"That person whose neighbor does not feel safe from his evil.\"<ref>{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|8|73|45}}</ref>\n\n===Rights of children===\n{{Main|Islam and children}}\n[[Sharia|Islamic law]] and the [[Hadith|traditions of Muhammad]] have laid out the rights of children in Islam. Children have the rights to be fed, clothed, and protected until reaching adulthood; rights to be treated equally among the [[sibling]]s; rights not to be forced by its step parents or its birth parents; and rights to education.<ref>I. A. Arshed. [http://www.islam101.com/sociology/parchild.htm Parent-Child Relationship in Islam]. Retrieved 2015-09-21</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sisters.islamway.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=104 |title=The Rights of Children In Islam |access-date=2016-02-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061024065203/http://sisters.islamway.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=104 |archive-date=2006-10-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.themodernreligion.com/index2.html Imam Al-Ghazali\u2019s views on children's education]</ref> Parents are also responsible for teaching their children basic [[Iman (concept)|Islamic beliefs]], [[Five Pillars of Islam|religious duties]] and [[Morality in Islam|good moral qualities]] like [[Adab (behavior)|proper mannerism]], [[honesty]], [[truth]]fulness, [[modesty]], and generosity.<ref>Campo (2009), p. 137</ref> The Quran forbids harsh and oppressive treatment of [[Orphan|orphaned children]] while urging kindness and [[justice]] towards them. It also condemns those who do not honor and feed the orphaned children (Quran {{cite quran|89|17-18|s=ns|b=n}}).<ref>Muhammad Shafi Usmani. ''[[Maariful Quran]]''. English trans. By [[Muhammad Taqi Usmani]]. Tafsir of 89:17-18</ref>\n\nMuhammad has been described as being very fond of children in general. In one Islamic tradition, Muhammad ran after [[Hussein ibn Ali|Hussein]], his grandson, in a game until he caught him.<ref name=Yust-72>{{cite book |last=Yust |first= Karen-Marie |title= Nurturing Child And Adolescent Spirituality: Perspectives from the World's Religious Traditions |url= |accessdate= |year= 2006 |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]] |location= |isbn= |pages=72\u20133}}</ref> He comforted a child whose pet nightingale had died.<ref>{{cite book |last=Phipps |first=William E |title=Muhammad and Jesus: A Comparison of the Prophets and Their Teachings |url= |accessdate= |year=1999 |publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group]] |location= |isbn= |page=120}}</ref> Muhammad played many games with children, joked with them and befriended them.<ref>{{cite book |last=Watt |first=William Montgomery |title=Muhammad Prophet and Statesman |url= |accessdate= |year=1974 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location= |isbn= |page=230}}</ref> Muhammad also showed love to children of other religions. Once he visited his Jewish neighbor's son when the child was sick.<ref name=Yust-72/>\n\n===Rights of the minorities===\n{{main|Islam and other religions|Dhimmi}}\nToday, [[Human rights in Islamic countries|minority rights in several Muslim countries]] are severely curtailed. [[History of Islam|Historically]], however, non-Muslim minorities have frequently enjoyed greater freedom in Muslim lands. This is evident from its [[Rashidun Caliphate|early beginnings]] through later [[caliphate|caliphates]], included the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] and [[Mughal Empire]]s. These freedoms were enjoyed by the [[people of the Book]], as well as by other non-Muslim peoples, many of whom still live in these lands today after over 1300 years of Muslim rule.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Penn |first1=Michael |title=Envisioning Islam: Syriac Christians and the Early Muslim World |date=August 15, 2017 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |isbn=0812224027}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Griffith |first1=Sydney |title=The Church in the Shadow of the Mosque: Christians and Muslims in the World of Islam |date=April 4, 2010 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=0691146284}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Hunter |first=Shireen |title=Islam and Human Rights: Advancing a U.S.-Muslim Dialogue |url= |accessdate= |year= 2005 |publisher= CSIS |location= |isbn= 9780892064717 |page=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Penn |first1=Michael |title=When Christians first met Muslims : a sourcebook of the earliest Syriac writings on Islam |date=March 21, 2015 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=0520284941 |edition=First}}</ref> The protection of minority rights is regarded as imperative under Islamic law which is in harmony with other international laws for the minority.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Marie-Luisa Frick |author2=Andreas Th. M\u00fcller |title=Islam and International Law: Engaging Self-Centrism from a Plurality of Perspectives |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DOGlx2dJvZYC&pg=PA313 |accessdate= |year=2013 |publisher=Martinus Nijhoff Publishers |location= |isbn=9789004233362 |page=313}}</ref>\n\n===Repudiation of racial discrimination===\nIn human history, [[Racism|racial discrimination]] has long been a cause of injustice.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=John Martin |editor1-last= Gillroy |editor2-first= Joe |editor2-last= Bowersox |title=The Moral Austerity of Environmental Decision Making: Sustainability, Democracy, and Normative Argument in Policy and Law |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=640pBPrfC5QC&pg=PA39 |accessdate=22 January 2016 |year= 2002 |publisher= Duke University Press |location= |isbn= 9780822383468 |page=39}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= San Juan |first=Epifanio |title=Working Through the Contradictions: From Cultural Theory to Critical Practice |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=POQd0XbRsOQC&pg=PA10 |year= 2004 |publisher=Bucknell University Press |location= |isbn= 9780838755709 |page=10}}</ref> One important aspect of Islam is that it regards human beings as ''equal children of Adam''. As a religion, Islam does not recognize the racial discrimination among people. In his [[Farewell Sermon]], Muhammad repudiated the discrimination based on [[Race (human_categorization)|race]] and color.<ref name=\"Encarta1\">{{cite book |title=Microsoft\u00ae Student 2008 [DVD] (Encarta Encyclopedia) |year=2007 |publisher=Microsoft Corporation |location=Redmond, WA |chapter=\"Muhammad (prophet)\"}}</ref> Islam recognizes no distinction among human beings based on color, language or [[Ethnicity|tribe]]. All are considered equal in receiving human rights and in discharge duties. According to Islamic teaching, no [[Privilege (social inequality)|privileged or chosen class]] exists except those having piety or moral excellence.<ref>Hashmi (2009), p. 62</ref> A Quranic injunction forbids the Muslims to underestimate others. Assuming that there will be natural differences in [[social status]] and income among individuals which is the natural outcome due to the differences in personal talents and efforts, a sense of [[Ummah|brotherhood towards fellow Muslims]] and a general sense of humanity towards every human being have been suggested to be cultured to further establish equality in society.<ref>Hashmi (2009), p. 62</ref>\n\n==Economic welfare==\n===Zakat===\n{{Main|zakat}}\nIn Islam, zakat is a form of compulsory alms-giving, and a religious obligation for those Muslims who are  financially affluent.<ref name=yaqaradxix>Yusuf al-Qaradawi (1999), Monzer Kahf (transl.), Fiqh az-Zakat, Dar al Taqwa, London, Volume 1, {{ISBN|978-967-5062-766}}, page XIX</ref> They are required to pay one-fortieth (2.5%) of their total income or money each year to those Muslims who are poor and helpless. The Quran says: 'And woe to those who join gods with Allah, who practice not regular charity, and who deny the Hereafter' ({{cite quran|41|6-7|s=ns|b=n}}). Zakat is considered by Muslims to be an act of piety through which one expresses concern for the [[Ihsan|well-being of fellow Muslims]],<ref name=\"Weiss-80\">{{cite book|author=Weiss, Anita M. |title=Islamic reassertion in Pakistan: the application of Islamic laws in a modern state|publisher=Syracuse University Press|year=1986|isbn=978-0-8156-2375-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/islamicreasserti00weis/page/80 80]|url=https://archive.org/details/islamicreasserti00weis|url-access=registration }}</ref> as well as preserving social harmony between the wealthy and the poor.<ref>{{cite book|author=Scott, James C.|title=Weapons of the weak: everyday forms of peasant resistance |publisher=Yale University Press|year=1985|isbn=978-0-300-03641-1|page=171|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=THCcW1gCe_QC&pg=PA171}}</ref> Zakat promotes a more equitable redistribution of wealth and fosters a sense of solidarity amongst members of the Ummah.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Jawad, Rana|title=Social welfare and religion in the Middle East: a Lebanese perspective|publisher=The Policy Press|year=2009|isbn=978-1-86134-953-8|page=60|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-NXbIU5KwUgC&pg=PA60}}</ref>\n\n===Sadaqah===\n{{Main|Sadaqah}}\nSadaqah means voluntary charity which is given out of compassion, love, friendship (fraternity), religious duty, or generosity.<ref>{{cite book |last=Said |first=Abdul Aziz |title=Contemporary Islam: Dynamic, Not Static |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4bs7g0O4eLYC&pg=PA145 |year=2006 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |location= |isbn=9780415770118 |page=145|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Both the Quran and the hadith have put much emphasis on spending money for the welfare of needy people. The Quran says: 'Spend something (in charity) out of the substance which We have bestowed on you, before Death should come to any of you' ({{cite quran|63|10|s=ns|b=n}}). One of the early teachings of Muhammad was that [[God in Islam|God]] expects men to be generous with their wealth and not to be miserly (Quran {{cite quran|107 |1|e=7|s=ns|b=n}}).<ref>{{cite book |author=Holt, P. M., Ann K. S. Lambton, and [[Bernard Lewis]] |title=The Cambridge History of Islam |year=2000 | publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] | isbn=978-0-521-21946-4 |page=32}}</ref> Accumulating wealth without spending them to address the needs of the poor is generally prohibited and admonished.<ref>{{cite book |editor=Matt Stefon|title=Islamic Beliefs and Practices |url=https://archive.org/details/islamicbeliefspr0000stef|url-access=registration|publisher=[[Britannica Educational Publishing]] |year=2010 |location=[[New York City|New York]] |isbn=978-1-61530-060-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/islamicbeliefspr0000stef/page/93 93]}}</ref>\n\n==Moral behavior==\n{{main|Morality in Islam}}\nIslamic tradition holds that moral qualities and good actions elevate the status of a man.<ref name=Nigosian116>{{cite book |last=Nigosian |first=S. A.  |title= Islam: Its History, Teaching, and Practices |url=https://archive.org/details/islamitshistoryt0000nigo |url-access=registration |year=2004 |publisher=[[Indiana University Press]] |location=[[Indiana]] |isbn= 0-253-21627-3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/islamitshistoryt0000nigo/page/116 116]}}</ref> The Quran and the hadith serve as the primary source of moral and ethical guidance in Islamic theology. Both the Quran and the hadith often speak in emphatic manners to instruct the Muslims to adopt a morally good character. In particular, respecting parents and elders, having love for the younger, greeting people in correct manner, showing kindness to fellow people, caring for the sick,  asking permission before entering into others' house, speaking the truth, and avoiding rude and false speech have been emphasized.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor=Juan E. Campo |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Islam |publisher=[[Facts On File]] |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-8160-5454-1|page=216}}</ref> The typical Islamic teaching is that imposing a penalty on an offender in proportion to their offense is permissible and just; but forgiving the offender is better. To go one step further by offering a favor to the offender is regarded the highest excellence.<ref name=Nigosian116/> Muhammad said, ''\"The best among you are those who have the best manners and character\"''.<ref>{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|8|73|56}}</ref> To the Muslims, the examples of moral virtues set by Muhammad and his companions serve as guidance both practically and theologically.\n\n==The Cairo Declaration on human rights==\n{{main|Cairo Declaration on Human Rights in Islam}}\nAdopted in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]], in 1990,<ref>Brems, E (2001). \"Islamic Declarations of Human Rights\". [https://books.google.com/books?id=INlkqsHpIFEC&pg=PA241 Human rights: universality and diversity: Volume 66 of International studies in human rights]. Martinus Nijhoff Publishers. pp. 241\u201384. {{ISBN|90-411-1618-4}}.</ref> the [[Cairo Declaration on Human Rights in Islam]] provides an overview on the Islamic perspective on human rights, and affirms [[Islamic]] [[sharia]] as its sole source. It declares its purpose to be \"general guidance for Member States of the [[OIC]] in the field of human rights\". The Declaration starts by saying \"All men are equal in terms of basic human [[dignity]]\" (but not equal \"human rights\") and it forbids \"discrimination on the basis of [[Race (classification of human beings)|race]], [[Skin colour|colour]], [[language]], [[belief]], [[gender]], [[religion]], [[political affiliation]], [[social status]] or other considerations\". The Declaration especially emphasizes on issues like \"preservation of human life\", \"[[right to privacy]]\", \"right to marriage\", prohibition of forceful conversion, protection against [[Arbitrary_arrest_and_detention |arbitrary arrest]] and [[torture]]. It also guarantees [[presumption of innocence]] until proven guilty, \"full right to freedom and self-determination\", and freedom of expression.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Islamic ethics]]\n* [[Peace in Islamic philosophy]]\n* [[Human rights in Islamic countries]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n[[Category:Human rights in Islam]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- keep the tone neutral, refrain from inserting own religious biases e.g. SAW/PBUH etc. Provide both sides of the argument including sanction of abuse, pedophilia, sexual slavery, subjugation of women, inhumane treatment of non-Muslims, wife beating, child abuse in Islam-->\n{{Islam}}\n'''Islamic teachings on humanity and human welfare''' have been codified in its central religious book known as the [[Quran]], which the [[Muslim]]s believe was [[Wahy|revealed]] by [[God]] for the mankind. These teachings have often been exemplified by Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]] as displayed in his [[Hadith|sayings]] and [[sunnah|practices]]. To the Muslims, Islam is what the Quran has instructed to do and how Muhammad has put them into practice. Thus, the understanding of any Islamic topic generally rely on these two.\n\n==Social welfare in Islam==\nIn Islamic tradition, the idea of social [[welfare]] has been presented as one of its principal values,<ref name=Stefon92>{{cite book |editor=Matt Stefon|title=Islamic Beliefs and Practices |url=https://archive.org/details/islamicbeliefspr0000stef|url-access=registration|publisher=[[Britannica Educational Publishing]] |year=2010 |location=[[New York City|New York]] |isbn=978-1-61530-060-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/islamicbeliefspr0000stef/page/92 92]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Palmer |first=Michael D. |title=Religion and Social Justice |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4W4fg2xZAOwC&pg=PA159 |accessdate=22 January 2016 |year=2012 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=9781405195478 |page=159}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://muslimcanada.org/welfare.htm |title=Social Welfare: A Basic Islamic Value |author=Anis Ahmad |date=1997 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> and the practice of social service at its various forms has been instructed and encouraged. A Muslim's [[D\u012bn|religious life]] remains incomplete if not attended by service to humanity.<ref name=Stefon92/> The following verse of the Quran is often cited to encapsulate the Islamic idea of social welfare:<ref>{{cite book |first1=John |last1= Corrigan |first2=Frederick |last2= Denny |first3=Martin S |last3= Jaffee |title=Jews, Christians, Muslims: A Comparative Introduction to Monotheistic Religions |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VahYCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA245 |accessdate=22 January 2016 |year=2016 |publisher=Routledge |location= |isbn=9781317347002 |page=245}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|It is not righteousness that ye turn your faces towards East or West; but it is righteousness to believe in Allah and the Last Day, and the Angels, and the Book and the Messengers; to spend of your substance, out of love for Him, for your kin, for orphans, for the needy, for the wayfarer, for those who ask, and for the ransom of slaves; to be steadfast in prayer, and practice regular charity, to fulfill the contracts which we have made; and to be firm and patient, in pain (or suffering) and adversity, and throughout all periods of panic. Such are the people of truth, the God fearing (Quran {{cite quran|2|177|s=ns|b=n}}).}}\n\nSimilarly, duties to [[parent]]s, [[Neighbourhood|neighbors]], relatives, sick people, the old, and the [[minority group]] have been defined in Islam. In a long [[hadith]] recorded in Hadith Qudsi (sacred hadith), it is said that God, on the [[Last Judgment|Day of Judgment]], will be displeased with those who do not care for the sick people, and who do not give food to those who ask. God will interrogate them and demand explanation from them. This hadith is seen as a reminder of human beings\u2019 obligation to respond to the needs of others.<ref>{{cite book |last= J. Cornell |first=Vincent |title=Voices of Islam: Voices of life : family, home, and society |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ixO4b6jlbLYC&pg=PA129 |accessdate= |year=2007  |publisher= Greenwood Publishing Group|location= |isbn=9780275987350 |page=129}}</ref> The individual, [[Family|the family]], the [[State (polity)|state]], and the [[Non-governmental organization]]s \u2014 all are responsible for the performance of social responsibilities, and for the promotion of social welfare. The Quran tells that the believers have been sent for the betterment of mankind, that they will promote what is good, and prevent what is wrong ({{cite quran|3|110|s=ns|b=n}}).<ref>[[Maariful Quran]] (exegesis of the Quran) by [[Muhammad Shafi Usmani]]. [[Karachi]]. Chapter 3.</ref> However, this is to be carried out in the best possible manner: no individuals honor should be injured, and no harm should arise out of it.<ref>Hashmi, Sohail H., ed. (2009). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=5LmXFpnp_bMC&pg=PA68 Islamic Political Ethics: Civil Society, Pluralism, and Conflict]''. Princeton University Press. p. 68. {{ISBN|9781400825370}}.</ref> In Islamic tradition, the family has a greater role to play in properly educating its members and providing them with moral schooling so as to make them good members of society. The state has the responsibility to preserve the [[human rights]] of its [[citizen]]s while various non-government institutions in a [[civil society]] are to carry out public services and [[Charity (practice)|charitable works]].<ref>Hashmi (2009), p. 68-9</ref>\n\n==Rights of various groups in Islam==\n===Rights of the parents and relatives===\nIn Islam, special importance has been attached to the service and rights of [[parent]]s. Respecting and obeying one's parents has been made a [[Fardh|religious obligation]], and ill-treatment to them is [[Haraam|forbidden in Islamic jurisprudence]] and Islamic tradition. With regard to the rights of parents, the Quranic injunction is to behave well with then, to take care of them especially in their old age, not to be rude to them, and to show highest respect to them.<ref>[[Muhammad Shafi Deobandi|Mufti Muhammad Shafi]]. ''[[Maariful Quran]]''. English trans. By [[Muhammad Taqi Usmani]]</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor=Juan E. Campo |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Islam |publisher=[[Facts On File]] |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-8160-5454-1|page=136}}</ref> <ref group=\"n\">The [[Quran]] says in this regard: \"Your Lord has decreed that you worship none but Him, and do good to parents. If any one of them or both of them reach old age, do not say to them a word of contempt and do not scold them, and address them with respectful words, and submit yourself before them in humility out of compassion, and say, \"My Lord, be merciful to them as they have brought me up in my childhood\"\"  ({{cite quran|17|23-24|s=ns|b=n}}).</ref> This injunction is to be applied regardless of parents' religious identity, that is, a Muslim person is to respect and serve their parents whether they be Muslim or non-Muslim.<ref>Cornell (2007), p. 97</ref> Hadith literature provides plenty of instances where Muhammad has commanded [[Sahabah|his companions]] to be good and kind to their parents and to serve them in the best possible manner.<ref>{{cite book |last= Cornell |first=Vincent J. |title=Voices of Islam: Voices of life : family, home, and society |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ixO4b6jlbLYC&pg=PA95 |accessdate=12 February 2016 |year=2007  |publisher= Greenwood Publishing Group |location= |isbn= 9780275987350 |page=95}}</ref> Insulting or misbehaving with one's parents has been declared a major sin.<ref>Cornell (2007), p. 98</ref> Mother, however, has been given priority over father in terms of receiving respect and service from children. The high status of mother in Islam is best exemplified by the saying of Muhammad that \"paradise is at the feet of your mothers\".  Similarly, importance has also been attached to the rights of [[Kinship|relatives]]. A two-fold approach is generally prescribed with regard to the duties to the relatives: keeping good relation with them, and offering financial help if necessary.<ref>{{cite book |last=Al-Sheha |first=Abdur Rahman |title=Human Rights in Islam and Common Misconceptions |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZRqe3iPwsTkC&pg=PA65 |location=Riyadh |pages=65}}</ref> Maintaining good relation with one's relatives has been emphasized, and severing ties with them has been admonished. It is said in the [[hadith]], \"The person who severs the bond of kinship will not enter Paradise.\"<ref>{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|8|73|13}}</ref>\n\n===Rights of the neighbors===\n{{Rquote|right|Gabriel kept on recommending me about treating the neighbors in a kind and polite manner, so much so that I thought that he would order me to make them my heirs.|'''[[Muhammad in Islam|Muhammad]]'''|''{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|8|73|44}}''}}\n\nRegardless of a [[Neighbourhood|neighbor]]'s religious identity, Islam tells the Muslims to treat their neighboring people in the best possible manners and not to cause any difficulty to them.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Abdelwahab |editor1-last=Bouhdiba |title=The Individual and Society in Islam: Volume 2 of The different aspects of Islamic culture |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xek6yZPAQjAC&pg=PA238 |accessdate= |year=1998 |publisher=UNESCO |location= |isbn=9789231027420 |page=238}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=al-Sheha |first=Abdur Rahman |title=Human Rights in Islam and Common Misconceptions |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZRqe3iPwsTkC&pg=PA75 |accessdate= |year= |publisher= |location=Riyadh |isbn= |pages=74\u20135}}</ref> The Quran tells the Muslims to stand by their neighbors in the latter's  everyday needs. Muhammad is reported as saying, \"A man is not a believer who fills his stomach while his neighbor is hungry.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sunnah.com/adab/6/12 |title=Al-Adab Al-Mufrad 112}}</ref> One typical [[hadith]] on neighbors reads as follows: Narrated Abu Shuraih: The Prophet said, \"By Allah, he does not believe! By Allah, he does not believe! By Allah, he does not believe!\" It was said, \"Who is that, O Allah's Apostle?\" He said, \"That person whose neighbor does not feel safe from his evil.\"<ref>{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|8|73|45}}</ref>\n\n===Rights of children===\n{{Main|Islam and children}}\n[[Sharia|Islamic law]] and the [[Hadith|traditions of Muhammad]] have laid out the rights of children in Islam. Children have the rights to be fed, clothed, and protected until reaching adulthood; rights to be treated equally among the [[sibling]]s; rights not to be forced by its step parents or its birth parents; and rights to education.<ref>I. A. Arshed. [http://www.islam101.com/sociology/parchild.htm Parent-Child Relationship in Islam]. Retrieved 2015-09-21</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sisters.islamway.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=104 |title=The Rights of Children In Islam |access-date=2016-02-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061024065203/http://sisters.islamway.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=104 |archive-date=2006-10-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.themodernreligion.com/index2.html Imam Al-Ghazali\u2019s views on children's education]</ref> Parents are also responsible for teaching their children basic [[Iman (concept)|Islamic beliefs]], [[Five Pillars of Islam|religious duties]] and [[Morality in Islam|good moral qualities]] like [[Adab (behavior)|proper mannerism]], [[honesty]], [[truth]]fulness, [[modesty]], and generosity.<ref>Campo (2009), p. 137</ref> The Quran forbids harsh and oppressive treatment of [[Orphan|orphaned children]] while urging kindness and [[justice]] towards them. It also condemns those who do not honor and feed the orphaned children (Quran {{cite quran|89|17-18|s=ns|b=n}}).<ref>Muhammad Shafi Usmani. ''[[Maariful Quran]]''. English trans. By [[Muhammad Taqi Usmani]]. Tafsir of 89:17-18</ref>\n\nMuhammad has been described as being very fond of children in general. In one Islamic tradition, Muhammad ran after [[Hussein ibn Ali|Hussein]], his grandson, in a game until he caught him.<ref name=Yust-72>{{cite book |last=Yust |first= Karen-Marie |title= Nurturing Child And Adolescent Spirituality: Perspectives from the World's Religious Traditions |url= |accessdate= |year= 2006 |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]] |location= |isbn= |pages=72\u20133}}</ref> He comforted a child whose pet nightingale had died.<ref>{{cite book |last=Phipps |first=William E |title=Muhammad and Jesus: A Comparison of the Prophets and Their Teachings |url= |accessdate= |year=1999 |publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group]] |location= |isbn= |page=120}}</ref> Muhammad played many games with children, joked with them and befriended them.<ref>{{cite book |last=Watt |first=William Montgomery |title=Muhammad Prophet and Statesman |url= |accessdate= |year=1974 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location= |isbn= |page=230}}</ref> Muhammad also showed love to children of other religions. Once he visited his Jewish neighbor's son when the child was sick.<ref name=Yust-72/>\n\n===Rights of the minorities===\n{{main|Islam and other religions|Dhimmi}}\nToday, [[Human rights in Islamic countries|minority rights in several Muslim countries]] are severely curtailed. [[History of Islam|Historically]], however, non-Muslim minorities have frequently enjoyed greater freedom in Muslim lands. This is evident from its [[Rashidun Caliphate|early beginnings]] through later [[caliphate|caliphates]], included the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] and [[Mughal Empire]]s. These freedoms were enjoyed by the [[people of the Book]], as well as by other non-Muslim peoples, many of whom still live in these lands today after over 1300 years of Muslim rule.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Penn |first1=Michael |title=Envisioning Islam: Syriac Christians and the Early Muslim World |date=August 15, 2017 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |isbn=0812224027}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Griffith |first1=Sydney |title=The Church in the Shadow of the Mosque: Christians and Muslims in the World of Islam |date=April 4, 2010 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=0691146284}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Hunter |first=Shireen |title=Islam and Human Rights: Advancing a U.S.-Muslim Dialogue |url= |accessdate= |year= 2005 |publisher= CSIS |location= |isbn= 9780892064717 |page=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Penn |first1=Michael |title=When Christians first met Muslims : a sourcebook of the earliest Syriac writings on Islam |date=March 21, 2015 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=0520284941 |edition=First}}</ref> The protection of minority rights is regarded as imperative under Islamic law which is in harmony with other international laws for the minority.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Marie-Luisa Frick |author2=Andreas Th. M\u00fcller |title=Islam and International Law: Engaging Self-Centrism from a Plurality of Perspectives |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DOGlx2dJvZYC&pg=PA313 |accessdate= |year=2013 |publisher=Martinus Nijhoff Publishers |location= |isbn=9789004233362 |page=313}}</ref>\n\n===Repudiation of racial discrimination===\nIn human history, [[Racism|racial discrimination]] has long been a cause of injustice.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=John Martin |editor1-last= Gillroy |editor2-first= Joe |editor2-last= Bowersox |title=The Moral Austerity of Environmental Decision Making: Sustainability, Democracy, and Normative Argument in Policy and Law |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=640pBPrfC5QC&pg=PA39 |accessdate=22 January 2016 |year= 2002 |publisher= Duke University Press |location= |isbn= 9780822383468 |page=39}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= San Juan |first=Epifanio |title=Working Through the Contradictions: From Cultural Theory to Critical Practice |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=POQd0XbRsOQC&pg=PA10 |year= 2004 |publisher=Bucknell University Press |location= |isbn= 9780838755709 |page=10}}</ref> One important aspect of Islam is that it regards human beings as ''equal children of Adam''. As a religion, Islam does not recognize the racial discrimination among people. In his [[Farewell Sermon]], Muhammad repudiated the discrimination based on [[Race (human_categorization)|race]] and color.<ref name=\"Encarta1\">{{cite book |title=Microsoft\u00ae Student 2008 [DVD] (Encarta Encyclopedia) |year=2007 |publisher=Microsoft Corporation |location=Redmond, WA |chapter=\"Muhammad (prophet)\"}}</ref> Islam recognizes no distinction among human beings based on color, language or [[Ethnicity|tribe]]. All are considered equal in receiving human rights and in discharge duties. According to Islamic teaching, no [[Privilege (social inequality)|privileged or chosen class]] exists except those having piety or moral excellence.<ref>Hashmi (2009), p. 62</ref> A Quranic injunction forbids the Muslims to underestimate others. Assuming that there will be natural differences in [[social status]] and income among individuals which is the natural outcome due to the differences in personal talents and efforts, a sense of [[Ummah|brotherhood towards fellow Muslims]] and a general sense of humanity towards every human being have been suggested to be cultured to further establish equality in society.<ref>Hashmi (2009), p. 62</ref>\n\n==Economic welfare==\n===Zakat===\n{{Main|zakat}}\nIn Islam, zakat is a form of compulsory alms-giving, and a religious obligation for those Muslims who are  financially affluent.<ref name=yaqaradxix>Yusuf al-Qaradawi (1999), Monzer Kahf (transl.), Fiqh az-Zakat, Dar al Taqwa, London, Volume 1, {{ISBN|978-967-5062-766}}, page XIX</ref> They are required to pay one-fortieth (2.5%) of their total income or money each year to those Muslims who are poor and helpless. The Quran says: 'And woe to those who join gods with Allah, who practice not regular charity, and who deny the Hereafter' ({{cite quran|41|6-7|s=ns|b=n}}). Zakat is considered by Muslims to be an act of piety through which one expresses concern for the [[Ihsan|well-being of fellow Muslims]],<ref name=\"Weiss-80\">{{cite book|author=Weiss, Anita M. |title=Islamic reassertion in Pakistan: the application of Islamic laws in a modern state|publisher=Syracuse University Press|year=1986|isbn=978-0-8156-2375-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/islamicreasserti00weis/page/80 80]|url=https://archive.org/details/islamicreasserti00weis|url-access=registration }}</ref> as well as preserving social harmony between the wealthy and the poor.<ref>{{cite book|author=Scott, James C.|title=Weapons of the weak: everyday forms of peasant resistance |publisher=Yale University Press|year=1985|isbn=978-0-300-03641-1|page=171|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=THCcW1gCe_QC&pg=PA171}}</ref> Zakat promotes a more equitable redistribution of wealth and fosters a sense of solidarity amongst members of the Ummah.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Jawad, Rana|title=Social welfare and religion in the Middle East: a Lebanese perspective|publisher=The Policy Press|year=2009|isbn=978-1-86134-953-8|page=60|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-NXbIU5KwUgC&pg=PA60}}</ref>\n\n===Sadaqah===\n{{Main|Sadaqah}}\nSadaqah means voluntary charity which is given out of compassion, love, friendship (fraternity), religious duty, or generosity.<ref>{{cite book |last=Said |first=Abdul Aziz |title=Contemporary Islam: Dynamic, Not Static |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4bs7g0O4eLYC&pg=PA145 |year=2006 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |location= |isbn=9780415770118 |page=145|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Both the Quran and the hadith have put much emphasis on spending money for the welfare of needy people. The Quran says: 'Spend something (in charity) out of the substance which We have bestowed on you, before Death should come to any of you' ({{cite quran|63|10|s=ns|b=n}}). One of the early teachings of Muhammad was that [[God in Islam|God]] expects men to be generous with their wealth and not to be miserly (Quran {{cite quran|107 |1|e=7|s=ns|b=n}}).<ref>{{cite book |author=Holt, P. M., Ann K. S. Lambton, and [[Bernard Lewis]] |title=The Cambridge History of Islam |year=2000 | publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] | isbn=978-0-521-21946-4 |page=32}}</ref> Accumulating wealth without spending them to address the needs of the poor is generally prohibited and admonished.<ref>{{cite book |editor=Matt Stefon|title=Islamic Beliefs and Practices |url=https://archive.org/details/islamicbeliefspr0000stef|url-access=registration|publisher=[[Britannica Educational Publishing]] |year=2010 |location=[[New York City|New York]] |isbn=978-1-61530-060-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/islamicbeliefspr0000stef/page/93 93]}}</ref>\n\n==Moral behavior==\n{{main|Morality in Islam}}\nIslamic tradition holds that moral qualities and good actions elevate the status of a man.<ref name=Nigosian116>{{cite book |last=Nigosian |first=S. A.  |title= Islam: Its History, Teaching, and Practices |url=https://archive.org/details/islamitshistoryt0000nigo |url-access=registration |year=2004 |publisher=[[Indiana University Press]] |location=[[Indiana]] |isbn= 0-253-21627-3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/islamitshistoryt0000nigo/page/116 116]}}</ref> The Quran and the hadith serve as the primary source of moral and ethical guidance in Islamic theology. Both the Quran and the hadith often speak in emphatic manners to instruct the Muslims to adopt a morally good character. In particular, respecting parents and elders, having love for the younger, greeting people in correct manner, showing kindness to fellow people, caring for the sick,  asking permission before entering into others' house, speaking the truth, and avoiding rude and false speech have been emphasized.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor=Juan E. Campo |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Islam |publisher=[[Facts On File]] |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-8160-5454-1|page=216}}</ref> The typical Islamic teaching is that imposing a penalty on an offender in proportion to their offense is permissible and just; but forgiving the offender is better. To go one step further by offering a favor to the offender is regarded the highest excellence.<ref name=Nigosian116/> Muhammad said, ''\"The best among you are those who have the best manners and character\"''.<ref>{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|8|73|56}}</ref> To the Muslims, the examples of moral virtues set by Muhammad and his companions serve as guidance both practically and theologically.\n\n==The Cairo Declaration on human rights==\n{{main|Cairo Declaration on Human Rights in Islam}}\nAdopted in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]], in 1990,<ref>Brems, E (2001). \"Islamic Declarations of Human Rights\". [https://books.google.com/books?id=INlkqsHpIFEC&pg=PA241 Human rights: universality and diversity: Volume 66 of International studies in human rights]. Martinus Nijhoff Publishers. pp. 241\u201384. {{ISBN|90-411-1618-4}}.</ref> the [[Cairo Declaration on Human Rights in Islam]] provides an overview on the Islamic perspective on human rights, and affirms [[Islamic]] [[sharia]] as its sole source. It declares its purpose to be \"general guidance for Member States of the [[OIC]] in the field of human rights\". The Declaration starts by saying \"All men are equal in terms of basic human [[dignity]]\" (but not equal \"human rights\") and it forbids \"discrimination on the basis of [[Race (classification of human beings)|race]], [[Skin colour|colour]], [[language]], [[belief]], [[gender]], [[religion]], [[political affiliation]], [[social status]] or other considerations\". The Declaration especially emphasizes on issues like \"preservation of human life\", \"[[right to privacy]]\", \"right to marriage\", prohibition of forceful conversion, protection against [[Arbitrary_arrest_and_detention |arbitrary arrest]] and [[torture]]. It also guarantees [[presumption of innocence]] until proven guilty, \"full right to freedom and self-determination\", and freedom of expression.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Islamic ethics]]\n* [[Peace in Islamic philosophy]]\n* [[Human rights in Islamic countries]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n[[Category:Human rights in Islam]]\n", "name_user": "2405:204:a01d:e3f9:cd0f:72c5:4423:eeea", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islam_and_humanity"}
{"title_page": "Thiare Casarez", "text_new": "{{short description|Mexican Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Thiare Casarez\n| image = Thiare Casarez - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships.jpg\n| imagesize = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| caption = Casarez at the 2013 IPC Athletics Championship\n| fullname = Thiare Jamilette Casarez Chinchillas\n| nicknames = \n| nationality = Mexican\n| sport = Athletics\n| event = Running\n| club = \n| collegeteam = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1993|01|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence = \n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| height =\n| weight =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[para-athletics]] (T37)}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{MEX}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 200 metres|400m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 200 metres|400m - T37]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Thiare Jamilette Casarez Chinchillas'''{{efn Spanish name|Casarez|Chinchillas}} (born 10 January 1993), known as '''Thiare Casarez''', is a parasport [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[Mexico]] competing mainly in category T37 sprint and middle distance racing events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://85.17.143.231/static/info/lyon/ENG/ZB/ZBB101A_LY2013AT@@@@@@@ENG_number=19652.htm|title=Thiare Casarez: Biography|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nCasarez was selected to represent Mexico at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Lyon. She competed in the Women's 100m, 200m and 400m T37 races. Although she failed to medal in the 100 metres, she took silver in both the 200 and 400 metre races.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Referencs==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|thiare-jamilette-casarez-chinchillas|Thiare Jamilette Casarez Chinchillas|old_id=1187792}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Casarez, Thiare}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Thiare Casarez\n| image = Thiare Casarez - 2013 IPC Athletics World Championships.jpg\n| imagesize = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| caption = Casarez at the 2013 IPC Athletics Championship\n| fullname = Thiare Jamilette Casarez Chinchillas\n| nicknames = \n| nationality = Mexican\n| sport = Athletics\n| event = Running\n| club = \n| collegeteam = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1993|01|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence = \n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place =\n| height =\n| weight =\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Women's [[para-athletics]] (T37)}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{MEX}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 200 metres|400m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]] |[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Women's 200 metres|400m - T37]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Thiare Jamilette Casarez Chinchillas'''{{efn Spanish name|Casarez|Chinchillas}} (born 10 January 1993), known as '''Thiare Casarez''', is a parasport [[Track and field|athlete]] from [[Mexico]] competing mainly in category T37 sprint and middle distance racing events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://85.17.143.231/static/info/lyon/ENG/ZB/ZBB101A_LY2013AT@@@@@@@ENG_number=19652.htm|title=Thiare Casarez: Biography|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nCasarez was selected to represent Mexico at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Lyon. She competed in the Women's 100m, 200m and 400m T37 races. Although she failed to medal in the 100 metres, she took silver in both the 200 and 400 metre races.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Referencs==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|1187792|Thiare Jamilette Casarez Chinchillas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Casarez, Thiare}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thiare_Casarez"}
{"title_page": "Subscription library", "text_new": "{{redirect|Proprietary library|a private library|private library}}\n{{lead too short|date=April 2016}}\n[[File:Vogel Za\u0142uski Library.jpg|thumb|right|[[Za\u0142uski Library|Biblioteka Za\u0142uskich]], built in [[Warsaw]] in the mid-18th century.]]\nA '''subscription library''' (also '''membership library''' or '''independent library''') is a [[library]] that is financed by private funds either from membership fees or endowments. Unlike a [[public library]], access is often restricted to members, but access rights can also be given to non-members, such as students.\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:The North Prospect of Mountague House JamesSimonc1715.jpg|thumb|right|The [[British Museum]] was established in 1751 and had a library containing over 50,000 books.]]\nIn the 18th century, there were virtually no public libraries in the sense in which we now understand the term i.e. libraries provided from public funds and freely accessible to all.<ref name=\"Kelly, Thomas 1966; p. 185\">Kelly, Thomas (1966); p. 185</ref> Only one important library in Britain, [[Chetham's Library]] in Manchester, was fully and freely accessible to the public.<ref name=\"Kelly, Thomas 1966; p. 185\"/> However, during the century, there came into being a whole network of library provision on a private or institutional basis.\n\nThe increase in secular literature at this time encouraged the establishment of commercial subscription libraries. Many small, private book clubs evolved into subscription libraries, charging high annual fees or requiring subscribing members to purchase shares. Subscription libraries would in turn use these earnings to expand their collections and later create their own publications.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|last1=Murray|first1=Stuart|title=The Library: An Illustrated History|date=2009|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing|location=Chicago, IL|isbn=9781616084530|page=148}}</ref> Unlike a [[public library]], access was often restricted to members. Some of the earliest such institutions were founded in late-17th century England, such as Chetham's Library in 1653, [[Innerpeffray Library]] in 1680 and [[Thomas Plume|Thomas Plume's Library]] in 1704. In the [[Colonial America|American colonies]], [[the Library Company of Philadelphia]] was started in 1731 by [[Benjamin Franklin]] in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia, PA]]. By paying an initial fee and annual dues, members had access to books, maps, fossils, antique coins, minerals, and scientific instruments.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first subscription library in Canada was formed in the 1800s at Niagara.\n\nThe materials available to subscribers tended to focus on particular subject areas, such as [[biography]], [[history]], [[philosophy]], [[theology]], and [[travel]], rather than works of fiction, particularly the novel.\n\nSubscription libraries were democratic in nature; created by and for communities of local subscribers who aimed to establish permanent collections of books and reading materials, rather than selling their collections annually as the circulating libraries tended to do, in order to raise funds to support their other commercial interests. Even though the subscription libraries were often founded by [[reading group|reading societies]], committees, elected by the [[subscription|subscribers]], chose books for the collection that were general, rather than aimed at a particular religious, political or professional group. The books selected for the collection were chosen because they would be mutually beneficial to the shareholders. The committee also selected the librarians who would manage the circulation of materials.<ref name=Forster>{{cite book|author1=Forster, Geoffrey|author2=Bell, Alan|title=The Cambridge History of Libraries in Britain and Ireland Volume 3: 1850\u20132000|date=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521780971|chapter=12 - The subscription libraries and their members}}</ref>{{rp|147\u2013148}}\n\nSubscription libraries were also referred to as 'proprietary' libraries due to the expectation that subscribers not only pay an annual fee, but that they must also invest in [[share (finance)|share]]s. These shares could be transferred by sale, gift or [[bequest]]. Many could not afford to purchase shares to become a member, even though they may have belonged to [[reading group|reading club]]s.<ref name=Forster />{{rp|148\u2013149}}\n\n===Circulating libraries===\n[[File:Donald McDonald, stationer, and his Circulating Library, Gulgong, 1870-1875, American and Australasian Photographic Company (5748710857).jpg|right|thumb| [[Circulating library]] and stationery shop, [[Gulgong]], Australia 1870.]]\nThe increasing production and demand for fiction promoted by rising literacy rates and the expansion of commercial markets, led to the rise of [[circulating library|circulating libraries]], which met a need that subscription libraries did not fulfill.\n\nWilliam Bathoe opened his commercial venture at two locations in London in 1737, and claimed to have been 'the Original Circulating library'.<ref name=Raven>{{cite book|last=Raven|first=James|title=The Cambridge History of Libraries in Britain and Ireland Volume 2: 1640\u20131850|date=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521792745|page=251|chapter=15 - Libraries for sociability: the advance of the subscription library}}</ref><ref name=picture1807>{{cite book |title=Picture of London, for 1807 |author=John Feltham |publisher=Richard Phillips |edition=8th |location=London |chapter= Circulating Libraries |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=j9MHAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA318 |author-link=John Feltham }}</ref> An early circulating library may even have been established in the mid-17th century; in an edition of \"Tom Tyler and his Wife\" in 1661 [[Francis Kirkman]] included a catalogue of 690 plays which he claimed to be ready to lend \"upon reasonable considerations\" from his premises in [[Westminster]].\n\nCirculating libraries charged subscription fees to users and offered serious subject matter as well as the popular novels, thus the difficulty in clearly distinguishing circulating from subscription libraries.<ref name=Eliot>{{cite book|last=Eliot|first=Simon|title=The Cambridge History of Libraries in Britain and Ireland Volume 3: 1850\u20132000|date=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521780971|pages=125\u2013126|chapter=11 - Circulating libraries in the Victorian age and after}}</ref> Occasionally subscription libraries called themselves 'circulating libraries', and vice versa.\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Many ordinary circulating libraries might call themselves 'subscription' libraries because they charged a subscription, while the earliest private subscription libraries, such as [[Leeds Library|Leeds]], [[Warrington Circulating Library|Warrington]], or Liverpool, describe themselves as 'circulating' libraries in their titles. Since many circulating libraries called themselves after the town where they were situated, it is often difficult to distinguish the type of a particular library, especially since many are only known to posterity from a surviving book label, with nothing but the name as identification\".<ref name=Manley>Manley, K.A. \"Booksellers, peruke-makers, and rabbit-merchants: the growth of circulating libraries in the eighteenth century.\" Libraries and the Book Trade: The formation of collections from the sixteenth to the twentieth century. Ed. Myers. New Castle, Delaware: Oak Knoll Press, 2000, p. 39.</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn Britain there were more than 200 commercial circulating libraries open in 1800, more than twice the number of subscription and private proprietary libraries that were operating at the same time. Many proprietors pandered to the most fashionable clientele, making much ado about the sort of shop they offered, the lush interiors, plenty of room and long hours of service.<ref name=Raven /> \"These 'libraries' would be called rental collections today.\"<ref>{{Citation |publisher = Scarecrow Press |isbn = 081082972X |location = Metuchen, N.J |title = History of libraries in the western world |author = Michael H. Harris |date = 1995}}</ref>\n\nWith the advent of free public libraries in the 19th century, most subscription libraries were replaced or taken over by the governing authorities.\n\n===Learned societies===\nIn London, numerous [[scientist|scientific dabblers]], amateurs, professionals concentrated in the comparatively small geographic area began to form a unique development - the [[learned society]]:\n\n<blockquote>\"These societies are voluntary associations of men and women who have come together because they are interested in the aims and objects which the societies serve and they feel that they can pursue those interests better as members of a society, rather than as individuals. The libraries therefore have been collected together for the purpose of serving the objects to which the various societies are dedicated and they do this, for the most part, by serving their members\".<ref name=Vernon>{{cite book|author1=Vernon, K. D. C.|title=The Libraries of London|date=1961|publisher=The Library Association|location=London|chapter=Learned Society Libraries}}</ref>{{rp|242}}</blockquote>\n\nLearned society libraries were private but were owned by larger groups of people. Materials were often lent or borrowed by qualified individuals or institutions outside the society. Societies were concerned mainly with the sciences, physical and biological, and often cooperated with other groups like the [[Royal Society]].\n\nExclusive subscription libraries, the world's oldest being the [[Chemical Society]] in London, was founded in 1841 for the general advancement of [[chemistry]]. Its primary objective was to guide and direct original research in chemistry and to disseminate that knowledge through [[debate]]s, lectures and its own ''[[Journal of the Chemical Society|journal]]''.<ref name=Vernon />{{rp|243\u2013246}}\n\n==Current membership libraries==\n===Australia===\n* 1833: [[Sydney Mechanics' School of Arts]]\n* 1839: [[Melbourne Athenaeum]]\n\n===Canada===\n[[File:Atwater Library of the Mechanics Institute of Montreal 02.jpg|thumb|right|Atwater Library of the Mechanics Institute of Montreal]]\n* 1828: [[Atwater Library of the Mechanics' Institute of Montreal]]\n\n===Ireland===\n* 1922: [[Central Catholic Library]]\n\n===United Kingdom===\n* 1653: [[Chetham's Library]]\n* 1680: [[Innerpeffray Library]]\n* 1704: [[Thomas Plume|Thomas Plume's Library]]\n* 1741: [[Leadhills|The Leadhills Miners' Library]]\n* 1768: [[Leeds Library]]\n* 1788: [[Linen Hall Library]]\n* 1793: [[The Literary and Philosophical Society of Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n* 1793: [[Westerkirk Parish Library]]\n* 1797: [[Liverpool Athenaeum|The Athenaeum (Liverpool)]]\n* 1799: [[Tavistock Subscription Library]]\n* 1800: [[Langholm Library]]\n* 1806: [[Portico Library]]\n* 1810: [[Plymouth Proprietary Library]]\n* 1812: [[Plymouth Athenaeum Library]]\n* 1813: [[Devon and Exeter Institution]]\n* 1816: [[Nottingham Subscription Library]]\n* 1818: [[Morrab Library]]\n* 1824: [[Bath Royal Literary and Scientific Institution]]\n* 1824: [[Ipswich Institute Reading Room and Library]]\n* 1832: [[Bradford Mechanics' Institute Library]]\n* 1832: [[Saffron Walden Town Library Society]]\n* 1834: [[Guildford Institute of the University of Surrey]]\n* 1839: [[Highgate Literary and Scientific Institution]]\n* 1841: [[London Library]]\n* 1854: [[Birmingham and Midland Institute]]\n* 1889: [[Saint Deiniol's Residential Library]]\n* 1894: [[Bishopsgate Institute]]\n* 1912: [[Armitt Library]]\n* 1928: [[Sybil Campbell Library]]\n\n===United States===\n* 1731: [[Library Company of Philadelphia]]\n* 1747: [[Redwood Library and Athenaeum]]\n* 1748: [[Charleston Library Society]]\n* 1753: [[Providence Athenaeum]]\n* 1754: [[New York Society Library]]\n* 1795: [[Lexington (Kentucky) Library Society]]\n* 1804: [[Social Law Library]]\n* 1807: [[Boston Athen\u00e6um]]\n* 1810: [[Salem Athenaeum]]\n* 1814: [[Athenaeum of Philadelphia]]\n* 1816: [[New Orleans Library Society]]\n* 1817: [[Portsmouth Athenaeum]]\n* 1820: [[General Society of Mechanics and Tradesmen of the City of New York]]\n* 1820: [[Maine Charitable Mechanics Association]] Library of Portland\n* 1820: [[New York Mercantile Library]]\n* 1826: [[The Institute Library (New Haven)]]\n* 1835: [[Mercantile Library of Cincinnati]]\n* 1846: [[St. Louis Mercantile Library Association]]\n* 1853: [[Congregational Library & Archives]]\n* 1854: [[San Francisco Mechanics' Institute]]\n* 1890: [[Lanier Library Association]] (Lanier Library of North Carolina)\n* 1897: [[Timrod Library]]\n* 1899: [[Athenaeum Music & Arts Library]] of La Jolla\n* 1900: Milford Mystery Library of Milford, Ohio <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geocaching.com/track/details.aspx?id=6195839|title=Discover MF: Milford Public Library|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* 1947: [[Mendocino Community Library]]\n* 1999: [[John Trigg Ester Library]]\n* 2015: [[Folio: The Seattle Athenaeum]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.folioseattle.org/|title=Folio {{!}} Home|website=folio|language=en|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Citation |publisher = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Co. |location = New York |title = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |date = 1910 |oclc = 14782424 |edition=11th |chapterurl =https://archive.org/stream/encyclopaediabri16chisrich#page/558/mode/1up |chapter =Libraries: Proprietary and Subscription Libraries }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://travel.nytimes.com/2008/03/07/travel/escapes/07athenaeum.html?em&ex=1205125200&en=3592d35201878ab2&ei=5087%0A \"Where Greek Ideals Meet New England Charm\"] - article about subscription libraries in [[New England]], from ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 7, 2008\n* The Library of Congress preserves a part of the lending stock of an early 20th-century commercial lending library in its [https://www.loc.gov/rr/rarebook/coll/tabard.html Tabard Inn Collection]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/11/business/yourmoney/11library.html \"Libraries of Gracious Reading, for Members Only\"]\n*[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-nottinghamshire-35831853 \"The fall and rise of subscription libraries\"]\n\n{{Libraries and library science}}\n\n[[Category:Subscription libraries| ]]\n[[Category:Types of library]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Proprietary library|a private library|private library}}\n{{lead too short|date=April 2016}}\n[[File:Vogel Za\u0142uski Library.jpg|thumb|right|[[Za\u0142uski Library|Biblioteka Za\u0142uskich]], built in [[Warsaw]] in the mid-18th century.]]\nA '''subscription library''' (also '''membership library''' or '''independent library''') is a [[library]] that is financed by private funds either from membership fees or endowments. Unlike a [[public library]], access is often restricted to members, but access rights can also be given to non-members, such as students.\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:The North Prospect of Mountague House JamesSimonc1715.jpg|thumb|right|The [[British Museum]] was established in 1751 and had a library containing over 50,000 books.]]\nIn the 18th century, there were virtually no public libraries in the sense in which we now understand the term i.e. libraries provided from public funds and freely accessible to all.<ref name=\"Kelly, Thomas 1966; p. 185\">Kelly, Thomas (1966); p. 185</ref> Only one important library in Britain, [[Chetham's Library]] in Manchester, was fully and freely accessible to the public.<ref name=\"Kelly, Thomas 1966; p. 185\"/> However, during the century, there came into being a whole network of library provision on a private or institutional basis.\n\nThe increase in secular literature at this time encouraged the establishment of commercial subscription libraries. Many small, private book clubs evolved into subscription libraries, charging high annual fees or requiring subscribing members to purchase shares. Subscription libraries would in turn use these earnings to expand their collections and later create their own publications.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|last1=Murray|first1=Stuart|title=The Library: An Illustrated History|date=2009|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing|location=Chicago, IL|isbn=9781616084530|page=148}}</ref> Unlike a [[public library]], access was often restricted to members. Some of the earliest such institutions were founded in late-17th century England, such as Chetham's Library in 1653, [[Innerpeffray Library]] in 1680 and [[Thomas Plume|Thomas Plume's Library]] in 1704. In the [[Colonial America|American colonies]], [[the Library Company of Philadelphia]] was started in 1731 by [[Benjamin Franklin]] in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia, PA]]. By paying an initial fee and annual dues, members had access to books, maps, fossils, antique coins, minerals, and scientific instruments.<ref name=\":0\" /> The first subscription library in Canada was formed in the 1800s at Niagara.\n\nThe materials available to subscribers tended to focus on particular subject areas, such as [[biography]], [[history]], [[philosophy]], [[theology]], and [[travel]], rather than works of fiction, particularly the novel.\n\nSubscription libraries were democratic in nature; created by and for communities of local subscribers who aimed to establish permanent collections of books and reading materials, rather than selling their collections annually as the circulating libraries tended to do, in order to raise funds to support their other commercial interests. Even though the subscription libraries were often founded by [[reading group|reading societies]], committees, elected by the [[subscription|subscribers]], chose books for the collection that were general, rather than aimed at a particular religious, political or professional group. The books selected for the collection were chosen because they would be mutually beneficial to the shareholders. The committee also selected the librarians who would manage the circulation of materials.<ref name=Forster>{{cite book|author1=Forster, Geoffrey|author2=Bell, Alan|title=The Cambridge History of Libraries in Britain and Ireland Volume 3: 1850\u20132000|date=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521780971|chapter=12 - The subscription libraries and their members}}</ref>{{rp|147\u2013148}}\n\nSubscription libraries were also referred to as 'proprietary' libraries due to the expectation that subscribers not only pay an annual fee, but that they must also invest in [[share (finance)|share]]s. These shares could be transferred by sale, gift or [[bequest]]. Many could not afford to purchase shares to become a member, even though they may have belonged to [[reading group|reading club]]s.<ref name=Forster />{{rp|148\u2013149}}\n\n===Circulating libraries===\n[[File:Donald McDonald, stationer, and his Circulating Library, Gulgong, 1870-1875, American and Australasian Photographic Company (5748710857).jpg|right|thumb| [[Circulating library]] and stationery shop, [[Gulgong]], Australia 1870.]]\nThe increasing production and demand for fiction promoted by rising literacy rates and the expansion of commercial markets, led to the rise of [[circulating library|circulating libraries]], which met a need that subscription libraries did not fulfill.\n\nWilliam Bathoe opened his commercial venture at two locations in London in 1737, and claimed to have been 'the Original Circulating library'.<ref name=Raven>{{cite book|last=Raven|first=James|title=The Cambridge History of Libraries in Britain and Ireland Volume 2: 1640\u20131850|date=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521792745|page=251|chapter=15 - Libraries for sociability: the advance of the subscription library}}</ref><ref name=picture1807>{{cite book |title=Picture of London, for 1807 |author=John Feltham |publisher=Richard Phillips |edition=8th |location=London |chapter= Circulating Libraries |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=j9MHAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA318 |author-link=John Feltham }}</ref> An early circulating library may even have been established in the mid-17th century; in an edition of \"Tom Tyler and his Wife\" in 1661 [[Francis Kirkman]] included a catalogue of 690 plays which he claimed to be ready to lend \"upon reasonable considerations\" from his premises in [[Westminster]].\n\nCirculating libraries charged subscription fees to users and offered serious subject matter as well as the popular novels, thus the difficulty in clearly distinguishing circulating from subscription libraries.<ref name=Eliot>{{cite book|last=Eliot|first=Simon|title=The Cambridge History of Libraries in Britain and Ireland Volume 3: 1850\u20132000|date=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521780971|pages=125\u2013126|chapter=11 - Circulating libraries in the Victorian age and after}}</ref> Occasionally subscription libraries called themselves 'circulating libraries', and vice versa.\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Many ordinary circulating libraries might call themselves 'subscription' libraries because they charged a subscription, while the earliest private subscription libraries, such as [[Leeds Library|Leeds]], [[Warrington Circulating Library|Warrington]], or Liverpool, describe themselves as 'circulating' libraries in their titles. Since many circulating libraries called themselves after the town where they were situated, it is often difficult to distinguish the type of a particular library, especially since many are only known to posterity from a surviving book label, with nothing but the name as identification\".<ref name=Manley>Manley, K.A. \"Booksellers, peruke-makers, and rabbit-merchants: the growth of circulating libraries in the eighteenth century.\" Libraries and the Book Trade: The formation of collections from the sixteenth to the twentieth century. Ed. Myers. New Castle, Delaware: Oak Knoll Press, 2000, p. 39.</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn Britain there were more than 200 commercial circulating libraries open in 1800, more than twice the number of subscription and private proprietary libraries that were operating at the same time. Many proprietors pandered to the most fashionable clientele, making much ado about the sort of shop they offered, the lush interiors, plenty of room and long hours of service.<ref name=Raven /> \"These 'libraries' would be called rental collections today.\"<ref>{{Citation |publisher = Scarecrow Press |isbn = 081082972X |location = Metuchen, N.J |title = History of libraries in the western world |author = Michael H. Harris |date = 1995}}</ref>\n\nWith the advent of free public libraries in the 19th century, most subscription libraries were replaced or taken over by the governing authorities.\n\n===Learned societies===\nIn London, numerous [[scientist|scientific dabblers]], amateurs, professionals concentrated in the comparatively small geographic area began to form a unique development - the [[learned society]]:\n\n<blockquote>\"These societies are voluntary associations of men and women who have come together because they are interested in the aims and objects which the societies serve and they feel that they can pursue those interests better as members of a society, rather than as individuals. The libraries therefore have been collected together for the purpose of serving the objects to which the various societies are dedicated and they do this, for the most part, by serving their members\".<ref name=Vernon>{{cite book|author1=Vernon, K. D. C.|title=The Libraries of London|date=1961|publisher=The Library Association|location=London|chapter=Learned Society Libraries}}</ref>{{rp|242}}</blockquote>\n\nLearned society libraries were private but were owned by larger groups of people. Materials were often lent or borrowed by qualified individuals or institutions outside the society. Societies were concerned mainly with the sciences, physical and biological, and often cooperated with other groups like the [[Royal Society]].\n\nExclusive subscription libraries, the world's oldest being the [[Chemical Society]] in London, was founded in 1841 for the general advancement of [[chemistry]]. Its primary objective was to guide and direct original research in chemistry and to disseminate that knowledge through [[debate]]s, lectures and its own ''[[Journal of the Chemical Society|journal]]''.<ref name=Vernon />{{rp|243\u2013246}}\n\n==Current membership libraries==\n===Australia===\n* 1833: [[Sydney Mechanics' School of Arts]]\n* 1839: [[Melbourne Athenaeum]]\n\n===Canada===\n[[File:Atwater Library of the Mechanics Institute of Montreal 02.jpg|thumb|right|Atwater Library of the Mechanics Institute of Montreal]]\n* 1828: [[Atwater Library of the Mechanics' Institute of Montreal]]\n\n===Ireland===\n* 1922: [[Central Catholic Library]]\n\n===United Kingdom===\n* 1653: [[Chetham's Library]]\n* 1680: [[Innerpeffray Library]]\n* 1704: [[Thomas Plume|Thomas Plume's Library]]\n* 1741: [[Leadhills|The Leadhills Miners' Library]]\n* 1768: [[Leeds Library]]\n* 1788: [[Linen Hall Library]]\n* 1793: [[The Literary and Philosophical Society of Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n* 1793: [[Westerkirk Parish Library]]\n* 1797: [[Liverpool Athenaeum|The Athenaeum (Liverpool)]]\n* 1799: [[Tavistock Subscription Library]]\n* 1800: [[Langholm Library]]\n* 1806: [[Portico Library]]\n* 1810: [[Plymouth Proprietary Library]]\n* 1812: [[Plymouth Athenaeum Library]]\n* 1813: [[Devon and Exeter Institution]]\n* 1816: [[Nottingham Subscription Library]]\n* 1818: [[Morrab Library]]\n* 1824: [[Bath Royal Literary and Scientific Institution]]\n* 1824: [[Ipswich Institute Reading Room and Library]]\n* 1832: [[Bradford Mechanics' Institute Library]]\n* 1832: [[Saffron Walden Town Library Society]]\n* 1834: [[Guildford Institute of the University of Surrey]]\n* 1839: [[Highgate Literary and Scientific Institution]]\n* 1841: [[London Library]]\n* 1854: [[Birmingham and Midland Institute]]\n* 1889: [[Saint Deiniol's Residential Library]]\n* 1894: [[Bishopsgate Institute]]\n* 1912: [[Armitt Library]]\n* 1928: [[Sybil Campbell Library]]\n\n===United States===\n* 1731: [[Library Company of Philadelphia]]\n* 1747: [[Redwood Library and Athenaeum]]\n* 1748: [[Charleston Library Society]]\n* 1753: [[Providence Athenaeum]]\n* 1754: [[New York Society Library]]\n* 1795: [[Lexington (Kentucky) Library Society]]\n* 1804: [[Social Law Library]]\n* 1807: [[Boston Athen\u00e6um]]\n* 1810: [[Salem Athenaeum]]\n* 1814: [[Athenaeum of Philadelphia]]\n* 1816: [[New Orleans Library Society]]\n* 1817: [[Portsmouth Athenaeum]]\n* 1820: [General Society of Mechanics and Tradesmen of the City of New York]]\n* 1820: [[Maine Charitable Mechanics Association]] Library of Portland\n* 1820: [[New York Mercantile Library]]\n* 1826: [[The Institute Library (New Haven)]]\n* 1835: [[Mercantile Library of Cincinnati]]\n* 1846: [[St. Louis Mercantile Library Association]]\n* 1853: [[Congregational Library & Archives]]\n* 1854: [[San Francisco Mechanics' Institute]]\n* 1890: [[Lanier Library Association]] (Lanier Library of North Carolina)\n* 1897: [[Timrod Library]]\n* 1899: [[Athenaeum Music & Arts Library]] of La Jolla\n* 1900: Milford Mystery Library of Milford, Ohio <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geocaching.com/track/details.aspx?id=6195839|title=Discover MF: Milford Public Library|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* 1947: [[Mendocino Community Library]]\n* 1999: [[John Trigg Ester Library]]\n* 2015: [[Folio: The Seattle Athenaeum]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.folioseattle.org/|title=Folio {{!}} Home|website=folio|language=en|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Citation |publisher = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Co. |location = New York |title = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |date = 1910 |oclc = 14782424 |edition=11th |c