{"title_page": "Marie Sharp's", "text_new": "[[File:Marie Sharp receiving HOF award @ 2016 NYC Hot Sauce Expo 03.JPG|thumb|<nowiki>Marie Sharp receiving Hall of Fame Award | 2016 NYC Hot Sauce Expo</nowiki>|alt=Marie Sharp receiving Hall of Fame award]]\n\n'''Marie Sharp's Fine Foods Ltd.,''' better known as '''Marie Sharp's''' is a 100% plant-based condiment and jam manufacturer based in [[Belize|the Stann Creek District of Belize]], Central America. The women-owned company is named after its founder [[Marie Sharp]] and is highly regarded for its world famous carrot-based [[habanero]] pepper sauce recipe.<ref name=\"HOF\">{{cite news|title=Hall of Fame For Marie Sharp |url=http://www.7newsbelize.com/sstory.php?nid=35875 |accessdate=12 December 2016 |publisher=7 News Belize |date=5 April 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417010652/http://www.7newsbelize.com/sstory.php?nid=35875 |archivedate=17 April 2016 |location=Belize City, Belize |url-status=dead }}</ref> The brand offers many varieties of sauces made from bases such as carrots, orange/grapefruit pulp, nopales, tamarind, mango, and pineapple combined with crushed habaneros.<ref>{{Cite web|title = FRONTLINE/WORLD . BELIZE - The Exile's Song . Reporter's Scrapbook: Follow the Beat - Non-Flash Version {{!}} PBS|url = https://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/stories/belize/scrapbook2d.html|website = [[PBS]]|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Travel Favorite -- Belize -- National Geographic|url = http://www.nationalgeographic.com/favorites/belize/reviews/644/|website = [[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]]|access-date = 2016-02-01|first = National Geographic|last = Society}}</ref> Marie Sharp's products are distributed in more than 20 countries and are widely available in restaurants and stores throughout Belize.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Centralamerica.Com - Know Belize - Food & Drink|url = http://www.centralamerica.com/belize/moon/bmofooddrink.htm|website = www.centralamerica.com|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref>  Her recipes are revered by top chefs and hot sauce aficionados worldwide.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Marie Sharp's Hot Sauces Belize.jpg|thumb|Several varieties of Marie Sharp's hot sauces]]\nThe company is privately owned by Marie Sharp, 79 years old in 2019, who began locally selling sauces on her 400-acre farm outside [[Dangriga]] in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Farm & Factory|url = http://www.mariesharpusa.com/farm-factory/|website = Marie Sharp's|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref> In 1985 a factory was built to meet growing demand, also serving as a popular tourist destination.<ref name=\":0\" /> The product was the first commercially successful agricultural product manufactured in and exported from Belize, under the name of \"'''Melinda\u2019s Hot Sauce'''\". Marie's recipe was the first habanero pepper sauce to achieve national distribution in the United States, with the [https://worldfiner.com/reese Reese Finer Foods] distribution network in 1989.  Once the market for the product had been established, the importer, Figueroa International Inc., who was marketing the sauce, trademarked the product name, effectively cutting Sharp out of her own business.<ref name=\"Research & Creative Activity (2007)\">{{cite journal|title=Bioprospecting and the Tale of Melinda's Hot Sauce|journal=Research & Creative Activity|date=Fall 2007|volume=30|issue=1, Food|url=http://www.indiana.edu/~rcapub/v30n1/melindas.shtml|accessdate=12 December 2016|publisher=Indiana University|location=Bloomington, Indiana|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808123656/http://www.indiana.edu/~rcapub/v30n1/melindas.shtml|archive-date=8 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gagnon|first=Deborah|date=Summer 2017|title=Can you keep a secret?  Marie Sharp: A Case Study|url=|journal=International Classroom Initiative Journal|volume=1|pages=51\u201361|via=Cognella Academic Publishing}}</ref>\n\nAfter a five-year struggle, Sharp gave up her original brand name, Melinda's Original Habanero Pepper sauce, in exchange for being released from her exclusive contract with the importer.  She then re-branded the product under her own name.<ref name=\"Research & Creative Activity (2007)\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Cheryl|title=In hot sauce hotbed of DFW, Figueroa brothers at Melinda's bringing more to the table|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/business/business/2016/06/17/in-hot-sauce-hotbed-of-dfw-figueroa-brothers-at-melinda-s-bringing-more-to-the-table|accessdate=12 December 2016|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|date=17 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161212024035/http://www.dallasnews.com/business/business/2016/06/17/in-hot-sauce-hotbed-of-dfw-figueroa-brothers-at-melinda-s-bringing-more-to-the-table|archivedate=12 December 2016|location=Dallas, Texas}}</ref>  Distribution has since expanded from Belize to much of Central and North America, Europe, Asia and Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 7 News Belize|url = http://7newsbelize.com/sstory.php?nid=33455|website = 7newsbelize.com|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Marie Sharp's Fine Foods Ltd. Proud Products of Belize|url = http://www.mariesharps-bz.com/business.html|website = www.mariesharps-bz.com|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref> In 2013, Sharp's entries at the [[Anuga Food Fair]] in [[Cologne]] made the prestigious \"Taste13 Showcase\" round and placed in the top three products at the world's largest food fair.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marie Sharp\u2019s Belizean Products Highlighted at World\u2019s Largest Food Show |url=http://www.ambergristoday.com/content/stories/2013/october/28/marie-sharps-belizean-products-worlds-largest-food-show |accessdate=12 December 2016 |newspaper=[[Ambergris Today]] |date=28 October 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626153626/http://www.ambergristoday.com/content/stories/2013/october/28/marie-sharps-belizean-products-worlds-largest-food-show |archivedate=26 June 2014 |location=San Pedro Town, Belize |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2014 Marie Sharp's sales totaled $3.8 million.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = The most magical place on Earth?|url = http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-ideas/best-of-travel/the-most-magical-place-on-earth/news-story/0dc431dfc4d0b120722063a8c1f744e0|website = [[News.com.au]]|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref> In 2016, the founder was inducted into the Hot Sauce Hall of Fame. The company also introduced their newest pepper sauce, \"Smokin' Marie's\", a smoked habanero sauce inspired by Alaskan smoked products.  A combination of orange, grapefruit, guava and craboo-wood is used to smoke the habaneros.<ref name=\"HOF\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=glJiIU1ii1o&t=129s|title=What is Craboo? {{!}} How to Smoke Habanero peppers \ud83c\udf36 using wood from retired Quince fruit trees|last=Touby|first=Michael|date=January 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2019, Gerry Sharp, Marie's husband and business partner later in life, died.  He was a [https://ambergriscaye.com/forum/ubbthreads.php/topics/534356/gerry-sharp-passes-citrus-pioneer-maries-husband.html citrus pioneer] in Belize and was instrumental in helping to shape the industry.\n\nOn January 27, 2019, Marie Sharp's oldest son, and well known and loved businessman, Michael Alexander Williams, Sr., 58, was murdered. Michael managed operations in Belize City for the company since the 1990s and he was instrumental to the continuing success of the Marie Sharp's brand in the countries largest market and throughout Central America.\n\nOn February 14, 2019, in partnership with the US Embassy in Belize, Marie Sharp announced the launch of a new pineapple pepper sauce, \"Pure Love\",  created to aid [https://bz.usembassy.gov/combating-gender-based-violence-through-partnership/ Combating Gender-Based Violence through Partnership]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bz.usembassy.gov/combating-gender-based-violence-through-partnership/|title=Combating Gender-Based Violence through Partnership|date=February 14, 2019|website=U.S. Embassy in Belize}}</ref> The proceeds of the sale of \u201cPure Love\u201d will go to Haven House\u2013a non-profit domestic violence shelter\u2013directly benefiting victims of gender-based violence and empowering them to take control and positively transform their lives.\n\n==Jelly and jam==\nIn 1982, finding that the farm had surplus fruit, Sharp visited local markets to get ideas of what products she and other farmers might be able to produce to increase their sales. Discovering that all the commercially produced [[jam]]s, [[Jelly (fruit preserves)|jellies]] and [[marmalade]]s were manufactured from non-tropical fruits, she recognized an opportunity. Experimenting with recipes, Sharp developed a product with higher fruit content than the [[US Food and Drug Administration]] required and began marketing her natural products made without preservatives. Marie Sharp\u2019s produces eleven types of preserves which are marketed locally and internationally.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Marie Sharp\u2019s Fine Foods Limited of Belize|journal=Tropical Fruits Newsletter|date=June 1999|issue=31|pages=13|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BG4OAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA13|accessdate=12 December 2016|publisher=Inter-American Institute for Cooperation on Agriculture|location=Port of Spain, Trinidad and Tobago}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of hot sauces]]\n* [[Scoville scale|Scoville heat scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.mariesharps.bz/}}\n\n{{Hot sauces|expand=yes}}\n\n{{portal bar|Food}}\n\n[[Category:Hot sauces]]\n[[Category:Brand name condiments]]\n[[Category:Condiment companies]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Belize]]\n[[Category:Belizean brands]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Marie Sharp receiving HOF award @ 2016 NYC Hot Sauce Expo 03.JPG|thumb|<nowiki>Marie Sharp receiving Hall of Fame Award | 2016 NYC Hot Sauce Expo</nowiki>|alt=Marie Sharp receiving Hall of Fame award]]\n\n'''Marie Sharp's Fine Foods Ltd.,''' better known as '''Marie Sharp's''' is a 100% plant-based condiment and jam manufacturer based in [[Belize|the Stann Creek District of Belize]], Central America. The women-owned company is named after its founder [[Marie Sharp]] and is highly regarded for its world famous carrot-based [[habanero]] pepper sauce recipe.<ref name=\"HOF\">{{cite news|title=Hall of Fame For Marie Sharp |url=http://www.7newsbelize.com/sstory.php?nid=35875 |accessdate=12 December 2016 |publisher=7 News Belize |date=5 April 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417010652/http://www.7newsbelize.com/sstory.php?nid=35875 |archivedate=17 April 2016 |location=Belize City, Belize |url-status=dead }}</ref> The brand offers many varieties of sauces made from bases such as carrots, orange/grapefruit pulp, nopales, tamarind, mango, and pineapple combined with crushed habaneros.<ref>{{Cite web|title = FRONTLINE/WORLD . BELIZE - The Exile's Song . Reporter's Scrapbook: Follow the Beat - Non-Flash Version {{!}} PBS|url = https://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/stories/belize/scrapbook2d.html|website = [[PBS]]|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Travel Favorite -- Belize -- National Geographic|url = http://www.nationalgeographic.com/favorites/belize/reviews/644/|website = [[National Geographic Channel|National Geographic]]|access-date = 2016-02-01|first = National Geographic|last = Society}}</ref> Marie Sharp's products are distributed in more than 20 countries and are widely available in restaurants and stores throughout Belize.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Centralamerica.Com - Know Belize - Food & Drink|url = http://www.centralamerica.com/belize/moon/bmofooddrink.htm|website = www.centralamerica.com|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref>  Her recipes are revered by top chefs and hot sauce aficionados worldwide.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Marie Sharp's Hot Sauces Belize.jpg|thumb|Several varieties of Marie Sharp's hot sauces]]\nThe company is privately owned by Marie Sharp, 79 years old in 2019, who began locally selling sauces on her 400-acre farm outside [[Dangriga]] in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Farm & Factory|url = http://www.mariesharpusa.com/farm-factory/|website = Marie Sharp's|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref> In 1985 a factory was built to meet growing demand, also serving as a popular tourist destination.<ref name=\":0\" /> The product was the first commercially successful agricultural product manufactured in and exported from Belize, under the name of \"'''Melinda\u2019s Hot Sauce'''\". Marie's recipe was the first habanero pepper sauce to achieve national distribution in the United States, with the [https://worldfiner.com/reese Reese Finer Foods] distribution network in 1989.  Once the market for the product had been established, the importer, Figueroa International Inc., who was marketing the sauce, trademarked the product name, effectively cutting Sharp out of her own business.<ref name=\"Research & Creative Activity (2007)\">{{cite journal|title=Bioprospecting and the Tale of Melinda's Hot Sauce|journal=Research & Creative Activity|date=Fall 2007|volume=30|issue=1, Food|url=http://www.indiana.edu/~rcapub/v30n1/melindas.shtml|accessdate=12 December 2016|publisher=Indiana University|location=Bloomington, Indiana|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808123656/http://www.indiana.edu/~rcapub/v30n1/melindas.shtml|archive-date=8 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gagnon|first=Deborah|date=Summer 2017|title=Can you keep a secret?  Marie Sharp: A Case Study|url=|journal=International Classroom Initiative Journal|volume=1|pages=51\u201361|via=Cognella Academic Publishing}}</ref>\n\nAfter a five-year struggle, Sharp gave up her original brand name, Melinda's Original Habanero Pepper sauce, in exchange for being released from her exclusive contract with the importer.  She then re-branded the product under her own name.<ref name=\"Research & Creative Activity (2007)\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hall|first1=Cheryl|title=In hot sauce hotbed of DFW, Figueroa brothers at Melinda's bringing more to the table|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/business/business/2016/06/17/in-hot-sauce-hotbed-of-dfw-figueroa-brothers-at-melinda-s-bringing-more-to-the-table|accessdate=12 December 2016|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|date=17 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161212024035/http://www.dallasnews.com/business/business/2016/06/17/in-hot-sauce-hotbed-of-dfw-figueroa-brothers-at-melinda-s-bringing-more-to-the-table|archivedate=12 December 2016|location=Dallas, Texas}}</ref>  Distribution has since expanded from Belize to much of Central and North America, Europe, Asia and Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 7 News Belize|url = http://7newsbelize.com/sstory.php?nid=33455|website = 7newsbelize.com|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Marie Sharp's Fine Foods Ltd. Proud Products of Belize|url = http://www.mariesharps-bz.com/business.html|website = www.mariesharps-bz.com|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref> In 2013, Sharp's entries at the [[Anuga Food Fair]] in [[Cologne]] made the prestigious \"Taste13 Showcase\" round and placed in the top three products at the world's largest food fair.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marie Sharp\u2019s Belizean Products Highlighted at World\u2019s Largest Food Show |url=http://www.ambergristoday.com/content/stories/2013/october/28/marie-sharps-belizean-products-worlds-largest-food-show |accessdate=12 December 2016 |newspaper=[[Ambergris Today]] |date=28 October 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140626153626/http://www.ambergristoday.com/content/stories/2013/october/28/marie-sharps-belizean-products-worlds-largest-food-show |archivedate=26 June 2014 |location=San Pedro Town, Belize |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2014 Marie Sharp's sales totaled $3.8 million.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = The most magical place on Earth?|url = http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-ideas/best-of-travel/the-most-magical-place-on-earth/news-story/0dc431dfc4d0b120722063a8c1f744e0|website = [[News.com.au]]|access-date = 2016-02-01}}</ref> In 2016, the founder was inducted into the Hot Sauce Hall of Fame. The company also introduced their newest pepper sauce, \"Smokin' Marie's\", a smoked habanero sauce inspired by Alaskan smoked products.  A combination of orange, grapefruit, guava and craboo-wood is used to smoke the habaneros.<ref name=\"HOF\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=glJiIU1ii1o&t=129s|title=What is Craboo? {{!}} How to Smoke Habanero peppers \ud83c\udf36 using wood from retired Quince fruit trees|last=Touby|first=Michael|date=January 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 14, 2019, Gerry Sharp, Marie's husband and business partner later in life, died.  He was a [https://ambergriscaye.com/forum/ubbthreads.php/topics/534356/gerry-sharp-passes-citrus-pioneer-maries-husband.html citrus pioneer] in Belize and was instrumental in helping to shape the industry.\n\nOn January 27, 2019, Marie Sharp's oldest son, and well known and loved businessman, Michael Alexander Williams, Sr., 58, was murdered. Michael managed operations in Belize City for the company since the 1990's and he was instrumental to the continuing success of the Marie Sharp's brand in the countries largest market and throughout Central America.\n\nOn February 14, 2019, in partnership with the US Embassy in Belize, Marie Sharp announced the launch of a new pineapple pepper sauce, \"Pure Love\",  created to aid [https://bz.usembassy.gov/combating-gender-based-violence-through-partnership/ Combating Gender-Based Violence through Partnership]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bz.usembassy.gov/combating-gender-based-violence-through-partnership/|title=Combating Gender-Based Violence through Partnership|date=February 14, 2019|website=U.S. Embassy in Belize}}</ref> The proceeds of the sale of \u201cPure Love\u201d will go to Haven House\u2013a non-profit domestic violence shelter\u2013directly benefiting victims of gender-based violence and empowering them to take control and positively transform their lives.\n\n==Jelly and jam==\nIn 1982, finding that the farm had surplus fruit, Sharp visited local markets to get ideas of what products she and other farmers might be able to produce to increase their sales. Discovering that all the commercially produced [[jam]]s, [[Jelly (fruit preserves)|jellies]] and [[marmalade]]s were manufactured from non-tropical fruits, she recognized an opportunity. Experimenting with recipes, Sharp developed a product with higher fruit content than the [[US Food and Drug Administration]] required and began marketing her natural products made without preservatives. Marie Sharp\u2019s produces eleven types of preserves which are marketed locally and internationally.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Marie Sharp\u2019s Fine Foods Limited of Belize|journal=Tropical Fruits Newsletter|date=June 1999|issue=31|pages=13|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BG4OAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA13|accessdate=12 December 2016|publisher=Inter-American Institute for Cooperation on Agriculture|location=Port of Spain, Trinidad and Tobago}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of hot sauces]]\n* [[Scoville scale|Scoville heat scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.mariesharps.bz/}}\n\n{{Hot sauces|expand=yes}}\n\n{{portal bar|Food}}\n\n[[Category:Hot sauces]]\n[[Category:Brand name condiments]]\n[[Category:Condiment companies]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Belize]]\n[[Category:Belizean brands]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marie_Sharp%27s"}
{"title_page": "Shahbaz (bird)", "text_new": "[[File:Standard of Cyrus the Great (Achaemenid Empire).svg|thumb|Derafsh-e Shahbaz-e-Talayi <br /> ({{lang-fa|\u062f\u0631\u0641\u0634 \u0634\u0627\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0627\u0632 \u0637\u0644\u0627\u06cc\u06cc}}) <br /> [[List of flags used by Iranian peoples|Standard]] of [[Cyrus the Great]] <br> ([[Zoroastrians in Iran|Zoroastrian]] [[Achaemenid Empire]]).]]\n\n'''Shahbaz''' ({{lang-fa|\u0634\u0627\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0627\u0632}}) is the name of a [[fable|fabled]] [[bird]]. It is like an [[eagle]], bigger than a [[Accipitrinae|hawk]] or [[falcon]]. The shahbaz lived in the [[Zagros]], [[Alborz]], and [[Ghafghaz]] mountains of [[Iran]]. In old [[Persian mythology]], Shahbaz was a god who helped the [[Iranian peoples|Iranians]] and guided [[Faravahar]] to [[Iran|Iran zamin]].\nDuring the Achaemenid era, especially at the time of Cyrus the Great, the Persian imperial flag was rectangular in shape, divided kite-like into four equal triangles alternating between two colors.\nIn the excavations at Persepolis archaeologists found a standard depicting a Shahbaz or golden eagle (Derafsh-e Shahbaz-e-Talayi) with open wings. The current belief is that this was the official symbol of Iran under Cyrus the Great and his heirs.\n\nShahbaz literally means \"royal falcon\".<ref name=\"Burton\">{{cite book|last=[[Richard Francis Burton|Burton]]|first=Sir Richard Francis|title=Falconry in the valley of the Indus|url=https://archive.org/details/falconryinvalle00burtgoog|year=1852}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Brill|first=E. J.|title=First Encyclopaedia of Islam 1913-1936}}</ref> Burton considered it to refer to the Goshawk, ''[[Northern goshawk|Accipiter gentilis]].''<ref name=\"Burton\"/> \"Shahbaz\" may also refer to the [[eastern imperial eagle]] which is known as imperial eagle ({{lang-fa|\u0639\u0642\u0627\u0628 \u0634\u0627\u0647\u06cc}}) which is the second largest (after the golden eagle) eagle in Iran.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Mythological birds of prey]]\n[[Category:Persian legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Zoroastrian legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Persian mythology]]\n[[Category:Asian mythology]]\n\n{{bird-stub}}\n{{mythology-stub}}\n{{Iran-hist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Standard of Cyrus the Great (Achaemenid Empire).svg|thumb|Derafsh-e Shahbaz-e-Talayi <br /> ({{lang-fa|\u062f\u0631\u0641\u0634 \u0634\u0627\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0627\u0632 \u0637\u0644\u0627\u06cc\u06cc}}) <br /> [[List of flags used by Iranian peoples|Standard]] of [[Cyrus the Great]] <br> ([[Zoroastrians in Iran|Zoroastrian]] [[Achaemenid Empire]]).]]\n\n'''Shahbaz''' ({{lang-fa|\u0634\u0627\u0647\u200c\u0628\u0627\u0632}}) is the name of a [[fable|fabled]] [[bird]]. It is like an [[eagle]], bigger than a [[Accipitrinae|hawk]] or [[falcon]]. The shahbaz lived in the [[Zagros]], [[Alborz]], and [[Ghafghaz]] mountains of [[Iran]]. In old [[Persian mythology]], Shahbaz was a god who helped the [[Iranian peoples|Iranians]] and guided [[Faravahar]] to [[Iran|Iran zamin]].\nDuring the Achaemenid era, especially at the time of Cyrus the Great, the Persian imperial flag was rectangular in shape, divided kite-like into four equal triangles alternating between two colors.\nIn the excavations at Persepolis archaeologists found a standard depicting a Shahbaz or golden eagle (Derafsh-e Shahbaz-e-Talayi) with open wings. The current belief is that this was the official symbol of Iran under Cyrus the Great and his heirs.\n\nShahbaz literally means \"royal falcon\".<ref name=\"Burton\">{{cite book|last=[[Richard Francis Burton|Burton]]|first=Sir Richard Francis|title=Falconry in the valley of the Indus|url=https://archive.org/details/falconryinvalle00burtgoog|year=1852}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Brill|first=E. J.|title=First Encyclopaedia of Islam 1913-1936}}</ref> Burton considered it to refer to the Goshawk, ''[[Northern goshawk|Accipiter gentilis]].''<ref name=\"Burton\"/> \"shahbaz\" may also refer to the [[eastern imperial eagle]] which is known as imperial eagle ({{lang-fa|\u0639\u0642\u0627\u0628 \u0634\u0627\u0647\u06cc}}) which is the second largest (after the golden eagle) eagle in Iran.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Mythological birds of prey]]\n[[Category:Persian legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Zoroastrian legendary creatures]]\n[[Category:Persian mythology]]\n[[Category:Asian mythology]]\n\n{{bird-stub}}\n{{mythology-stub}}\n{{Iran-hist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ambrosiawater", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shahbaz_(bird)"}
{"title_page": "2009 MSBL season", "text_new": "{{Infobox sports season\n| title = 2009 MSBL season\n| league = [[State Basketball League]]\n| sport = [[Basketball]]\n| duration = 13 March \u2013 18 July (Regular season)<br>25 July \u2013 22 August (Finals)\n| no_of_games = 26\n| no_of_teams = 14\n| season = Regular season\n| minor_premiers = [[Lakeside Lightning]]\n| MVP = Luke Meyer (Buccaneers)\n| MVP_link = State Basketball League Most Valuable Player Award\n| top_scorer = Chris Lynch (Redbacks)\n| top_scorer_link = \n| finals = Finals\n| finals_champ = [[Lakeside Lightning]]\n| finals_runner-up = [[Perry Lakes Hawks]]\n| grand_final_MVP = [[Luke Payne]] (Lightning)\n| grand_final_MVP_link = State Basketball League Grand Final Most Valuable Player Award\n| seasonslistnames = MSBL\n| prevseason_link = 2008 MSBL season\n| prevseason_year = 2008\n| nextseason_link = 2010 MSBL season\n| nextseason_year = 2010\n}}\n\nThe '''2009 MSBL season''' was the 21st season of the Men's [[State Basketball League]] (SBL). The regular season began on Friday 13 March and ended on Saturday 18 July. The finals began on Saturday 25 July and ended on Saturday 22 August, when the [[Lakeside Lightning]] defeated the [[Perry Lakes Hawks]] in the MSBL Grand Final.\n\n==Regular season==\nThe regular season began on Friday 13 March and ended on Saturday 18 July after 19 rounds of competition.\n\n===Standings===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"0\" border=\"1\" width=\"35%\" style=\"font-size:95%; text-align:center\"\n|-\n! width=\"5%\" rowspan=2| {{Tooltip| Pos | Position}}\n|-\n! width=\"10%\" | Team\n! width=\"5%\" | {{Tooltip| W | Games won}}\n! width=\"5%\" | {{Tooltip| L | Games lost}}\n|-\n!1\n|align=left|[[Lakeside Lightning]] || 22 || 4\n|-\n!2\n|align=left|[[Goldfields Giants]] || 21 || 5\n|-\n!3\n|align=left|[[Joondalup Wolves|Wanneroo Wolves]] || 18 || 8\n|-\n!4\n|align=left|[[Geraldton Buccaneers]] || 18 || 8\n|-\n!5\n|align=left|[[Cockburn Cougars]] || 18 || 8\n|-\n!6\n|align=left|[[Perry Lakes Hawks]] || 17 || 9\n|-\n!7\n|align=left|[[Kalamunda Eastern Suns]] || 11 || 15\n|-\n!8\n|align=left|[[Perth Redbacks]] || 11 || 15\n|- bgcolor=\"#cccccc\"\n| || || ||\n|-\n!9\n|align=left|[[Stirling Senators]] || 11 || 15\n|-\n!10\n|align=left|[[Willetton Tigers]] || 10 || 16\n|-\n!11\n|align=left|[[Rockingham Flames]] || 8 || 18\n|-\n!12\n|align=left|[[East Perth Eagles]] || 8 || 18\n|-\n!13\n|align=left|[[South West Slammers]] || 6 || 20\n|-\n!14\n|align=left|[[Mandurah Magic]] || 3 || 23\n|-\n|}\n\n==Finals==\nThe finals began on Saturday 25 July and ended on Saturday 22 August with the MSBL Grand Final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://websites.sportstg.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-5011-0-444185-0&sID=78732&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=9524844 |title=Final match-Ups Set |work=SportsTG.com |date=19 July 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404073501/https://websites.sportstg.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-5011-0-444185-0&sID=78732&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=9524844 |archivedate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://websites.sportstg.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-5011-0-444185-0&sID=78732&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=9533583 |title=Quarter Final Times & Dates Announced |work=SportsTG.com |date=20 July 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404073647/https://websites.sportstg.com/assoc_page.cgi?c=1-5011-0-444185-0&sID=78732&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=9533583 |archivedate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Bracket===\n{{8TeamBracket-Tennis3| RD1= Quarter Finals\n| RD2= Semi Finals\n| RD3= Grand Final\n\n| score-width= 25\n| team-width= 150\n\n| RD1-seed1= 1\n| RD1-team1= '''[[Lakeside Lightning]]'''\n| RD1-score1-1= 89\n| RD1-score1-2= '''105'''\n| RD1-score1-3= '''98'''\n| RD1-seed2= 8\n| RD1-team2= [[Perth Redbacks]]\n| RD1-score2-1= '''96'''\n| RD1-score2-2= 81\n| RD1-score2-3= 85\n\n| RD1-seed3= 4\n| RD1-team3= '''[[Geraldton Buccaneers]]'''\n| RD1-score3-1= '''111'''\n| RD1-score3-2= 97\n| RD1-score3-3= '''1